t substance they call yenom from their distributor (who frequently performs less tasks and labor than the actual workers), and transferring the made-up numbers into something they call a “bank account”. This also refers to the facility where the fake computer-generated numbers are counted and kept safe from others, called a bank. Their belief system suggests that yenom is the god that determines an individual’s survival or quality of life. The Nacirema culture puts yenom at the forefront, which opens up an extreme variety of uses for and phrases of the word bank, such as use as both adjective and verb. The polysemy of the Nacirema’s word bank can be seen in its completely unrelated context, referring to a pile of mud where the edges of their rivers collide with. This can also be used as a verb meaning to heap something up. For some reason, the Nacirema belief system and culture assigns many different unrelated meanings to the same series of sounds. The variety of words and phrases using “bank” also speaks to their obsession with yenom, a made-up mostly invisible substance that the Nacirema allow to control their lives. They use this substance as justification for making some of their population starve or be homeless, once again suggesting their central obsession with making things harder than they have to be.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: E:)%0a%3c (:Category: LanguageOfTheNacirema:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
